TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Just Noticeable Difference in Complexity of Jobs
AU  - Globerson, Shlomo
Y1  - 1977/02/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.23.6.606
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.23.6.606
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 606
EP  - 611
VL  - 23
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper investigates the magnitude of Nonrepetitive Time (NRT) change that will be subjectively perceived as significant. NRT is a previously developed index of job complexity and NRT change can be identified with the ?Just Noticeable Difference? of job complexity. Together, they enable the job designer to evaluate the nature of the jobs and to compare the complexity of one job to another. The results indicate that two jobs would be subjectively considered to be significantly different one from the other in terms of their complexity, if the NRT index of one of them is larger by approximately 100 percent than the other.
AB  - This paper investigates the magnitude of Nonrepetitive Time (NRT) change that will be subjectively perceived as significant. NRT is a previously developed index of job complexity and NRT change can be identified with the ?Just Noticeable Difference? of job complexity. Together, they enable the job designer to evaluate the nature of the jobs and to compare the complexity of one job to another. The results indicate that two jobs would be subjectively considered to be significantly different one from the other in terms of their complexity, if the NRT index of one of them is larger by approximately 100 percent than the other.
